{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:06:38.045379+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a thorough understanding of the repository. Here is the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Runtime Profiles\n\nThe project defines five runtime profiles:\n\n| Profile | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| **local** | Development environment that works even without network connectivity. |\n| **local-dev** | Connects from a local machine to the DEV (remote) environment. |\n| **dev** | Used when deploying to the Development environment. |\n| **staging** | Used when deploying to the Staging environment. |\n| **live** | Used when deploying to the Live (production) environment. |\n\nThese profiles are documented in the `README.md` under the *Runtime Profiles* section but their concrete configuration files (e.g., `application-local.yml`, `application-dev.yml`, etc.) are not present in the current repository snapshot — they would typically reside in the `core:core-api` module’s resources.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Developer Setup for Linting and Running Tests\n\n### 1. Linting\n\n- **Format tool:** Spring Java Format (`io.spring.javaformat` plugin, version `0.0.47`), configured via `lint.gradle` which applies the plugin and its Gradle plugin dependency to all subprojects.\n- **Indentation:** Spaces (configured in `.springjavaformatconfig` as `indentation-style=spaces`).\n- **Pre-commit hook:** Run the following command to enable a Git hook that executes `./gradlew checkFormat` before every commit:\n  ```bash\n  git config core.hookspath .githooks\n  ```\n  The hook itself (`.githooks/pre-commit`) simply runs `$GIT_DIR/gradlew checkFormat`.\n- **IntelliJ IDEA integration:** The README recommends installing the [Spring Java Format IntelliJ IDEA plugin](https://github.com/spring-io/spring-javaformat#intellij-idea) so that IDE formatting matches the project style.\n\n### 2. Running Tests\n\nThe project defines five test suites with specific tag-based filtering (configured in `build.gradle` under the `testing { suites { ... } }` block):\n\n| Task | Tags included | Tags excluded | Purpose |\n|------|---------------|---------------|---------|\n| `test` (default) | — | `develop`, `restdocs` | The CI‑intended test collection. |\n| `unitTest` | — | `develop`, `context`, `restdocs` | Fast, dependency‑free unit tests. |\n| `contextTest` | `context` | — | Integration tests that load a Spring context. |\n| `restDocsTest` | `restdocs` | — | Generates AsciiDoc documentation via Spring REST Docs. |\n| `developTest` | `develop` | — | Tests that should **not** be run in CI (e.g., work‑in‑progress). |\n\n- **IDE setting:** The README advises configuring IntelliJ IDEA to run tests using **IntelliJ IDEA** (instead of Gradle) under *Build, Execution, Deployment → Build Tools → Gradle → Run tests using* for a smoother local test execution experience.\n- **CI pipeline:** The GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`) runs `checkFormat` (lint) and `test` on pushes/PRs to `main`.\n\n### 3. Project Overview\n\n- **Build system:** Gradle (wrapper included) with Java 25 (toolchain).\n- **Java version in CI:** Java 21 (Ubuntu, Adopt).\n- **Subprojects:** `core:core-api`, `core:core-enum`, `storage:db-core`, `tests:api-docs`, `support:logging`, `support:monitoring`, `clients:client-example`.\n- **Dependency versions** are centralized in `gradle.properties`.\n\nIn short, a developer should:\n1. Run `git config core.hookspath .githooks` to activate automatic formatting on commit.\n2. Set their IDE to use IntelliJ IDEA for running tests.\n3. Use `./gradlew test` to run the CI‑compatible test suite, or `unitTest`/`contextTest`/`restDocsTest`/`developTest` for targeted test groups.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1275, "prompt_tokens": 9689, "total_tokens": 10964, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 384, "rejected_